 the “glass half full.” They inspire the reader to reflect on life’s struggles and to find within themselves a sense of optimism, perhaps when they least expect to. Kathryn Carter’s concluding essay places these stories in the context of contemporary discourses of illness and healing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOvariesxCancerxPatientszCanadavBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Diseases / Cancer.2bisacsh1 aCarter, Kathryn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElit, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElit, Laurie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLavery, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458163440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554581634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554581634/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles